LAS VEGAS (AP) — The school board for metro Las Vegas plans next Thursday to consider whether to terminate Superintendent Jesus Jara’s employment contract.An agenda  posted Friday for the Clark County School District trustees includes discussion and possible action on “termination of convenience” of Jara’s contract.Three board members requested the agenda item on Jara’s contract, which the board last May voted 4-3 to extend.It wasn’t immediately clear why the three trustees wanted to discuss Jara’s contract.Jara has faced criticism over his handling of the COVID-19 pandemic, including the decision to operate with 100% distance learning for about a year beginning in March 2020, as well as the school reopening process, the Las Vegas Review-Journal reported.Coronavirus pandemicRoll up your sleeves: Kids' turn arrives for COVID-19 shotsCOVID-19's global death toll tops 5 million in under 2 yearsEXPLAINER: What to know about vaccines for kids aged 5-11COVID vaccine for younger kids already being packed, shippedADVERTISEMENTRegarding the board’s intention to consider his contract, Jara said Friday he intends to focus on working for students and educators until he’s directed otherwise.The board also is scheduled to consider removing Linda Cavazos as its president.Jara has been superintendent since 2018, and his annual salary is $320,000.